class_name RoomLayouts
extends Object
## Hand-designed room layouts, as ASCII.
##
## Why ASCII: a TileMapLayer stores its cells as an opaque PackedInt32Array, which
## is unreadable and unreviewable in a diff. These maps are the source of truth —
## edit them here and re-run tools/gen_rooms.gd. The generated .tscn files are
## still ordinary Godot scenes you can open and edit; if you do, edit them here
## too or the next regen will overwrite you.
##
## Legend:
##   #  solid tile
##   =  one-way platform (jump up through it, land on top)
##   .  empty
##   P  player entry
##   X  exit
##   g  grunt spawn    b  brute spawn    d  dart spawn    E  Overseer (miniboss)
##   S  shrine SPOT — a candidate altar. The delve lights only some per run
##      (seeded), so a spot is a possibility, not a promise.
##   C  crumbling platform (gives way a beat after you land, re-forms later)
##   v  spikes (pit floors: falling in stays survivable, but now it costs)
##
## Design budget, and it is not advisory — tools/gen_rooms.gd runs a reachability
## analysis and refuses to build a room that violates it:
##   Jump rises 109 px = 3.4 tiles, so a 3-row step lands and a 4-row step does
##   not. Platforms therefore sit on TIERS at rows 14, 11, 8, 5, 2 (the floor is
##   row 17). Horizontal reach is ~218 px = 6.8 tiles, so consecutive tiers must
##   come within ~6 columns of each other or the climb dead-ends.
##
## The first version of this file put every platform 4 rows up. Nothing errored;
## the rooms simply could not be climbed, and it took a playtest to notice. That
## is why the generator now proves it instead of trusting the comment.
##
## Rooms are 58x18 playable; the generator adds a 1-tile border, giving 60x20
## tiles = 1920x640 px, matching the fixed camera used everywhere else.

const WIDTH: int = 58
const HEIGHT: int = 18

